Unwoke investingOne thing I have sometimes wondered about is why there are =
a lot of investment options that lean explicitly to the left politically, b=
ut not a lot that lean to the right. Socially responsible investing, and en=
vironmental, social and governance investing, are booming businesses and ha=
ve a more or less progressive flavor, but there is not really an equivalent=
 on the conservative side.You could, I think, have a sort of sociological m=
odel for this: People who manage investments tend to be highly educated pro=
fessionals in big coastal cities, a demographic that skews progressive. Som=
e of them will care about the environment and social justice and will run=
=C2=A0ESG funds; others won=E2=80=99t care that much and will run =E2=80=9C=
regular,=E2=80=9D non-ESG, active or passive funds; but few will be social =
conservatives or climate-change skeptics who want to start explicitly right=
-wing funds. I think there=E2=80=99s something to this model, but not all t=
hat much; it=E2=80=99s not like the financial industry is overwhelmingly ov=
ertly progressive.Or you could have sort of a simple model where there are =
two political parties of investing, as it were:=09The left position is that=
 companies should do good in various progressive ways, and you should try t=
o send your money to the good ones and not the bad ones.=09The right positi=
on is that companies should maximize profits and shareholder returns, witho=
ut trying to do good for the world.In this model, ESG and socially responsi=
ble investing are necessarily leftish positions, while the rightish equival=
ent is just=C2=A0normal investing, just buying the stocks you think will go=
 up without regard to their environmental and social records.[3] If you=E2=
=80=99re a progressive, you think =E2=80=9Ccompanies should be good steward=
s of the environment=E2=80=9D and buy ESG funds; if you=E2=80=99re a conser=
vative, you think =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t care if companies are good stewa=
rds of the environment as long as they make money=E2=80=9D and buy, just, r=
egular funds. There is no third position like =E2=80=9CI think companies sh=
ould be bad stewards of the environment=E2=80=9D; the neutral, unmarked, de=
fault=C2=A0option is the conservative one.I think this model is roughly cor=
rect but also not fully satisfying. You can see a little of it in the polit=
ical reaction to ESG and socially responsible investing, where the right-wi=
ng position is often to use legislation or regulation to=C2=A0ban or=C2=A0r=
estrict socially responsible investing and require investors to focus exclu=
sively on financial results. The traditional conservative position on the p=
urpose of the corporation is that the purpose of the corporation is to make=
 money, so the politically conservative approach to investing is to ignore =
politics and just pick the stocks that will go up the most.But while that i=
s the traditional view, I don=E2=80=99t think it really captures modern U.S=
. conservatism.=C2=A0With modern U.S. conservatism you=E2=80=99d expect to =
see more explicitly anti-progressive, anti-woke, anti-environmental, genera=
lly politically engaged investment options: not =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll buy =
the most profitable companies whether or not they use fossil fuels=E2=80=9D=
 but =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll buy the fossil fuel companies to own the libs.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And now there is a bit of that. From the=C2=A0Wall Street Jo=
urnal:A small group of conservative money managers is trying to catch up to=
 investment funds that for years have catered to those concerned about clim=
ate change, diversity or animal rights. =E2=80=A6The American Conservative =
Values ETF, which was started just before last fall=E2=80=99s election, has=
 seen its assets under management more than triple so far this year, from a=
bout $3 million to more than $9 million. The growth =E2=80=9Cabsolutely val=
idates that demand exists,=E2=80=9D according to Bill Flaig, the founder an=
d chief executive of the fund=E2=80=99s suburban-Washington management firm=
, Ridgeline Research.The fund that Mr. Flaig helps oversee =E2=80=9Cboycott=
s=E2=80=9D Facebook Inc., Apple Inc., Google parent Alphabet Inc. and more =
than 20 other companies that it views as overly progressive in their corpor=
ate politics. =E2=80=A6In April, the American Conservative Values ETF dropp=
ed from its portfolio Atlanta-based corporations Delta Air Lines Inc. and C=
oca-Cola Co., after their executives criticized a new Georgia voting law th=
at civil-rights groups have argued will make voting harder.BlackRock=E2=80=
=99s ESG exchange-traded funds had inflows of $8.6 billion in the fourth qu=
arter of 2020, meaning that BlackRock brings=C2=A0in more ESG ETF money eve=
ry trading hour than this conservative ETF has brought in in its history, b=
ut it=E2=80=99s a start. Or here=E2=80=99s another one:Two ETFs run by 2ndV=
ote Advisers LLC near Nashville have grown in the past month from about $6 =
million to roughly $25 million, representatives say. Money managers at the =
firm say they hope they will surpass $100 million by the end of the year af=
ter adding more portfolio choices and courting pension funds in conservativ=
e-leaning states.=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s an investment option for unwoke inve=
stors,=E2=80=9D said Andy Puzder, who is on the firm=E2=80=99s advisory boa=
rd. =E2=80=9CWe believe that companies that focus on profit make more than =
companies that don=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9DThat sounds like my traditional model=
, where woke investors care about social and political issues and unwoke on=
es just care about profit, but in fact 2ndVote doesn=E2=80=99t just care ab=
out profit:2ndVote Advisers started offering two ETFs after last year=E2=80=
=99s presidential election. One fund caters to investors who feel strongly =
about opposing abortion, while the other is targeted at supporters of gun r=
ights.The funds use a =E2=80=9Csocial scoring system=E2=80=9D that looks at=
 a variety of company information, including direct and indirect donations,=
 activities and stated policies, sponsorship of political and advocacy-rela=
ted events, donations by corporate leaders, and lobbying efforts for or aga=
inst various issues on the state and federal level.=E2=80=9CCompanies that =
focus on profit are worth more than companies that don=E2=80=99t=E2=80=9D i=
s sort of the traditional conservative view; =E2=80=9Ccompanies that oppose=
 abortion rights are worth more than companies that support them=E2=80=9D i=
s the new view.Cathie, Larry, ElonI don=E2=80=99t know if this is true, and=
 honestly I assume it isn=E2=80=99t,[4] but it=E2=80=99s too amazing not to=
 print here:Ark Invest CEO Cathie Wood =E2=80=A6 weighed in on the effect o=
f Tesla CEO Elon Musk=E2=80=99s recent pronouncements on Bitcoin, claiming =
that Musk was likely pressured to switch investment strategies on Bitcoin b=
y his firm=E2=80=99s shareholders such as BlackRock Inc., an American multi=
national investment management corporation. =E2=80=9CI believe what happene=
d is after he took a position on Bitcoin, he got pushback from institutiona=
l shareholders like BlackRock. You've got Larry Fink beating drum on climat=
e change. I don't think he expected that. But I think he'll come back to th=
e mix.=E2=80=9D said Wood.My model of Larry Fink and BlackRock is that they=
 control vast sums of money that they invest in every single company and so=
 can=E2=80=99t spend a lot of time thinking about the specific business dec=
isions of=C2=A0any particular company. Where BlackRock can add value as an =
investor is by thinking systemically: Instead of worrying about some widget=
 company=E2=80=99s market share (meaningless, to BlackRock, since it owns a=
ll of the company=E2=80=99s competitors), it spends its time thinking about=
 systemic risks to all of the companies it owns. One risk that  BlackRock c=
ares about a lot is climate change, which makes sense: If the world becomes=
 uninhabitable for humans that will probably be  bad for every company=E2=
=80=99s profits, and BlackRock owns every company.=C2=A0And so BlackRock ca=
n go to every company and say =E2=80=9Cbe better about climate change.=E2=
=80=9D But again BlackRock necessarily operates at a rather high level of g=
enerality =E2=80=94=C2=A0owning every company, etc.=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 it might not be obvious, at that level, what every company should=C2=A0do=
=C2=A0about climate change. I suppose you could call up the coal companies =
and say =E2=80=9Cstop mining coal,=E2=80=9D and BlackRock is  doing a tiny =
bit of that. But are you going to call up a social media company and give i=
t nuanced recommendations, grounded=C2=A0in its particular business needs, =
about reducing executive travel and locating its servers in places that use=
 more renewable energy? Seems like a lot of work.On the other hand you can =
have some simple blanket climate policies. And if you think =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
as many people, apparently including  Elon Musk last week, do =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that Bitcoin mining is=C2=A0very bad for the environment, then a blanket=
 policy for all companies saying =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t=C2=A0accept Bitcoin=
 for payment=E2=80=9D seems reasonable enough. It=E2=80=99s not like any co=
mpanies need to accept Bitcoin for payment; even Bitcoin Pizza doesn=E2=80=
=99t accept Bitcoin for payment.=C2=A0(To be clear, whether Bitcoin is that=
 bad is itself controversial, and  Wood has argued that Bitcoin is=C2=A0goo=
d=C2=A0for the environment, because it creates off-peak demand for electric=
ity that can make renewable generation economically viable.) So you really =
could just about imagine it being logical for Larry Fink =E2=80=94=C2=A0Tes=
la=E2=80=99s third-biggest shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0to call up Elon Musk =
and tell him =E2=80=9Chey, I am an environmental guy, I like your electric =
cars, but knock it off with the Bitcoin.=E2=80=9DThat said, my model of Elo=
n Musk is that he absolutely absolutely absolutely does not care even the t=
iniest bit what BlackRock thinks, and has no reason to care. Musk owns 17.7=
% of Tesla; BlackRock owns 5.2%. Tesla is in the S&P 500 index, so BlackRoc=
k=E2=80=99s index funds are stuck with it. If Musk needs money, he can easi=
ly raise it by doing at-the-market offerings to enthusiastic retail investo=
rs rather than bothering with BlackRock; in fact,  he did that when Tesla w=
as added to the S&P 500, which is ordinarily the best time for a company to=
 raise money from index-y institutional=C2=A0investors like BlackRock. Tesl=
a=E2=80=99s governance style is =E2=80=9CElon Musk whimsy=E2=80=9D rather t=
han, like, =E2=80=9Ctraditional good governance,=E2=80=9D and the company=
=E2=80=99s personal identification with Musk is so strong, and Musk is so s=
trange, that he just has no reason or inclination to care about what his in=
stitutional shareholders think. I assume if Elon Musk got a call from Larry=
 Fink to talk about climate change, he=E2=80=99d=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=
=80=99re boring!=E2=80=9D and hang up.And in fact Musk did get bored enough=
 of being anti-Bitcoin that he was back to being kind of pro-Bitcoin yester=
day,  tweeting about his diamond hands, though also somewhat anti-Bitcoin, =
tweeting memes making fun of Bitcoin fans=C2=A0because that is also fun. It=
 doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0feel like the influence of staid institutional invest=
ors, you know?In general I am  very=C2=A0fond of  theories =E2=80=94=C2=A0e=
ven somewhat conspiratorial theories =E2=80=94=C2=A0suggesting that massive=
 institutional investors exercise enormous unseen power over global compani=
es. I just don=E2=80=99t believe those theories about Tesla.=C2=A0Elsewhere=
There will be a Bloomberg Opinion Clubhouse chat about Bitcoin and Elon Mus=
k at 4 p.m. New York time today, if you=E2=80=99re interested; I will proba=
bly be there with Roy Bahat, Liam Denning, Lionel Laurent and Olga Kharif. =
Here=E2=80=99s a link.Things happenApollo Co-Founder  Harris Steps Back Aft=
er Missing Out on CEO. Morgan Stanley CEO  Shakes Up Leadership With Eyes o=
n a Successor. JPMorgan Eyes  $100 Million Payday on Trade Linked to Aramco=
 Deal. Colonial Pipeline CEO Tells Why He Paid Hackers a $4.4 Million Ranso=
m.=C2=A0Oatly IPO Prices at $17 a Share, Notching $10 Billion Valuation.=C2=
=A0ByteDance Founder  Steps Down as CEO Ahead of Mega IPO.=C2=A0SPAC Sellof=
f Bruises Individual Investors. European Companies, Flush With Cash, Turn t=
o Stock Buybacks. The Reinvention of  Canary Wharf. The Pleasures of Learne=
dLeague and the Spirit of Trivia.=C2=A0$ASS Coin Billionaire: Tales From th=
e  Fringe of the Crypto Craze. =E2=80=98Please Help,=E2=80=99 Beg Those Who=
 Lost $2 Million to  Fake Elon Musks.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0S=
tuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe a=
t this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg =
newsletters here. Thanks!=C2=A0[1] Some Googling suggests that some FSA loa=
ns are prepayable without penalty and some are not. But the program (Sectio=
n 1005 of the American Rescue Plan Act of 2021)=C2=A0does not call for modi=
fying the loans, just providing money to pay them back on their terms, so I=
 assume that either there are no prepayment penalties, or that the governme=
nt will pay them and they=E2=80=99re still not enough to make the banks who=
le.[2] This is a small-bank problem; big banks just don=E2=80=99t have enou=
gh disadvantaged farmer loans to care. =E2=80=9CRepresentatives for Goldman=
 Sachs, JPMorgan Chase and Citigroup said that the debt relief program had =
not been on their radar and that they had not been lobbying against it,=E2=
=80=9D notes the Times.[3] There is a=C2=A0vein of ESG theory that says tha=
t the good environmental and social stocks will also go up more =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that having=C2=A0good environmental policies is good for long-term va=
lue, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I don=E2=80=99t think that believing or disbel=
ieving that is=C2=A0essential to any of these arguments.[4] To be clear,=C2=
=A0it=E2=80=99s true that she said it (at a Bloomberg BusinessWeek event, a=
s Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Eric Balchunas tweeted); I just have no particular re=
ason to think her assertion about Musk and Fink is true.
